        "description": "The Ultra Realistic Surfing Simulator allows for a close-to-reality surfing experience from any place imaginable. It is a two-part system where motion sensed by a board is translated into wave motions of an ocean diorama.",
        "steps": [
            "Assemble the plywood surfboard by tracing a paper stencil onto the wood, then cutting it out and gluing/screwing it together.",
            "Laser cut the diorama parts from 3mm and 2mm plexiglas, ensuring to use a good grade plexiglas to avoid blurriness when in contact with acrylic glue.",
            "Assemble the diorama by gluing the plexiglas pieces together in the following order: bottom plate, short sides, long sides. Seal all edges from the inside and allow ample curing time for the glue.",
            "Test the diorama for waterproofing by filling it with water and checking for leaks, sealing any leaks with more glue or silicon.",
            "Fill the waterproof diorama with blue colored water (1/3 full) and then top it off with transparent baby oil, ensuring all air bubbles are removed. Seal the filling holes with transparent silicon.",
            "Assemble the diorama base using plexiglass, gears, bolts, washers, nuts, aluminum sleeve, and the servomotor, staggering the gears to distribute the load. Attach the wavebox to the base, ensuring it is not firmly attached and can tilt.",
            "Wire the circuits for the transmitter (on the board) and receiver (for the diorama) following the provided wiring plan, or use a wire instead of a radio transmitter to connect the board and diorama.",
            "Upload the provided Arduino codes to the respective Arduino boards, ensuring that all required libraries are installed. The transmitter code reads the board angle and sends it to the receiver, which controls the servo motor.",
            "Adjust the transmitter code by fixing the transmitter to the surfboard, plugging the Arduino back to the computer, and fine-tuning the angle readings to match the board's orientation.",
            "Enjoy the surfing!"
        ]
